nited Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Brooke","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Brook  , which preserves a trace of the Old English dative singular case, originally used after a preposition (e.g. ‘at the brook’).","History: In 1650, Robert and Mary Mainwaring Brooke brought ten children and a number of servants with them from England to MD, where Robert became governor. Although the fourteen known contemporary Brooke immigrants in VA included Robert's brothers Richard and Humphrey, the relationships of the others are unknown. Brooke family memorials remain in the Anglican church at Whitchurch, Hampshire, England."],"variants":[{"name":"Brook","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived by a brook, stream, water-meadows or low, marshy ground, from Middle English <i>brook</i>, Old English <i>brōc</i> ‘brook, stream’; or a habitational name from any of various places called with this word, such as Brook (Kent, Rutland) or Brooke (Norfolk).","North German: topographic name for someone who lived by a water meadow or marsh, from Low German <i>brook</i> (cognate with German   Bruch   ‘swamp’ and Old English <i>brōc</i>; see 1 above).","Americanized form of Dutch <b>Broek</b>: topographic name from <i>broek</i>, a cognate of 2 above."]}]},{"name":"Christina","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Simplified form of Latin <i>Christiana</i>, feminine form of <i>Christianus</i> (  see  Christian  ), or a Latinized form of Middle English <i>Christin</i> ‘Christian’ (Old English <i>christen</i>, from Latin)."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":13,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Christina Brooke was born in 1442, in Leighton by Neston, Cheshire, England, her father, Richard Brooke, was 42 and her mother, Margerie Lee, was 37. She married Bartholomew Hall in 1462, in Ipswich, Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1463, at the age of 21."},"et":{"1442–1463":"1442–1463","1430–1475":"1430–1475","1440–1463":"1440–1463","1463–1502":"1463–1502","1400–1440":"1400–1440","1405–Female":"1405–Surnud","1502":"1502","about 1429":"umbes 1429","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1442":"1442","1475":"1475","1463":"1463","1430":"1430","1462":"1462","1440":"1440","1405":"1405","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, England","Leighton by Neston, Cheshire, England":"Leighton by Neston, Cheshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1442–1463":"1442–1463","1430–1475":"1430–1475","1440–1463":"1440–1463","1463–1502":"1463–1502","1400–1440":"1400–1440","1405–Female":"1405–Kuollut","1502":"1502","about 1429":"noin 1429","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1442":"1442","1475":"1475","1463":"1463","1430":"1430","1462":"1462","1440":"1440","1405":"1405","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, England","Leighton by Neston, Cheshire, England":"Leighton by Neston, Cheshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1442–1463":"1442–1463","1430–1475":"1430–1475","1440–1463":"1440–1463","1463–1502":"1463–1502","1400–1440":"1400–1440","1405–Female":"1405–Décédée","1502":"1502","about 1429":"environ 1429","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1442":"1442","1475":"1475","1463":"1463","1430":"1430","1462":"1462","1440":"1440","1405":"1405","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk,